805
00:58:05.586 --> 00:58:08.786
He loved loud music, it relaxed him.

806
00:58:10.456 --> 00:58:13.286
He had purposefully installed...

807
00:58:14.746 --> 00:58:16.626
What is a "speaker"? Sorry.

808
00:58:17.626 --> 00:58:20.246
A powerful speaker... sorry.

809
00:58:21.036 --> 00:58:22.996
He worked a lot, it was noisy...

810
00:58:23.206 --> 00:58:26.536
Mrs Solidor says
you ended the interview over that.


811
00:58:26.706 --> 00:58:29.166
- Is that true?
- She never said that.


812
00:58:29.336 --> 00:58:30.636
If the defense

813
00:58:31.246 --> 00:58:34.416
keeps reacting to every question,

814
00:58:34.586 --> 00:58:36.496
I'll be very irritated.

815
00:58:37.626 --> 00:58:39.586
Mrs Voyter, answer the question.

816
00:58:42.246 --> 00:58:44.876
The music was just very loud.

817
00:58:45.036 --> 00:58:47.206
And when it started over,

818
00:58:47.376 --> 00:58:50.416
I realized it wasn't going to stop.

819
00:58:51.916 --> 00:58:54.876
That made discussion difficult.

820
00:58:55.036 --> 00:58:56.916
So I...

821
00:58:57.956 --> 00:58:59.416
I preferred to stop.

822
00:59:00.036 --> 00:59:02.336
And I was tired, yes.

823
00:59:02.496 --> 00:59:03.746
And I felt a bit...

824
00:59:05.586 --> 00:59:07.456
woozy, from the wine.

825
00:59:08.206 --> 00:59:11.746
Yet once alone, you didn't ask
him to explain his behavior?


826
00:59:13.536 --> 00:59:15.746
As I said, it was habitual.

827
00:59:15.916 --> 00:59:17.246
No.

828
00:59:17.456 --> 00:59:20.586
You entertaining
an attractive young woman


829
00:59:20.746 --> 00:59:24.246
while he toiled upstairs
was neither habitual, nor neutral.


830
00:59:24.416 --> 00:59:27.246
He knew you liked women.
You'd recently cheated.


831
00:59:27.416 --> 00:59:28.996
That's beside the point.

832
00:59:29.226 --> 00:59:30.116
And sexist.

833
00:59:30.206 --> 00:59:33.076
I'd have said the same
if she were an attractive man.


834
00:59:33.206 --> 00:59:36.916
Excuse me, but this couple's
conflicts matter here.


835
00:59:37.126 --> 00:59:39.996
There's something
a bit strange in this situation.


836
00:59:40.166 --> 00:59:43.746
You say you went upstairs
to your room to work and sleep.


837
00:59:43.916 --> 00:59:47.416
Right below the attic
with the deafening music.


838
00:59:47.586 --> 00:59:50.746
Music that had made
the interview impossible.


839
00:59:50.916 --> 00:59:53.166
In that big house,
you chose that spot?


840
00:59:53.376 --> 00:59:57.126
Yes, that's where I work.
I always work in bed.


841
00:59:59.586 --> 01:00:02.836
When Samuel came to talk to you,
you didn't complain?


842
01:00:02.996 --> 01:00:06.286
Deafening music overhead
is hardly normal.


843
01:00:08.206 --> 01:00:09.706
I'm used to it, I don't mind.

844
01:00:09.876 --> 01:00:12.626
I wanted to work, 
I had my earplugs.

845
01:00:12.786 --> 01:00:13.836
It was normal.

846
01:00:14.626 --> 01:00:16.626
I can work in any situation.

847
01:00:16.836 --> 01:00:19.496
You said you were tired,
woozy from the wine.


848
01:00:19.666 --> 01:00:21.536
Yet you wanted to work?

849
01:00:21.746 --> 01:00:22.746
Yes.

850
01:00:22.876 --> 01:00:24.626
And I did. Not for long.

851
01:00:24.786 --> 01:00:26.336
A translation was due.

852
01:00:26.496 --> 01:00:28.746
I wanted to finish it before resting.

853
01:00:29.336 --> 01:00:33.376
As I said, I can work
in any environment, any condition.


854
01:00:33.586 --> 01:00:36.746
Apparently you can also rest
anywhere, anytime.


855
01:00:36.916 --> 01:00:39.036
So all was well with the world.

856
01:00:44.126 --> 01:00:45.146
That's all.

857
01:00:48.746 --> 01:00:50.126
No further questions.

858
01:00:53.206 --> 01:00:55.376
Daniel, that's not what you told us.

859
01:00:55.536 --> 01:00:58.456
Zoe Solidor saw you
leave the house after she left.


860
01:00:58.626 --> 01:01:01.916
And your mom says
she spoke to your dad after that.


861
01:01:03.536 --> 01:01:04.746
I got mixed up.

862
01:01:05.586 --> 01:01:06.836
You got mixed up.

863
01:01:13.086 --> 01:01:15.286
Indeed there is a problem, Daniel.

864
01:01:15.456 --> 01:01:16.456
Right?

865
01:01:16.586 --> 01:01:19.286
You couldn't be two places at once.

866
01:01:20.786 --> 01:01:23.166
I think I went back inside.

867
01:01:25.916 --> 01:01:30.086
What bothers me is how sure you were
before the reenactment.


868
01:01:30.456 --> 01:01:32.666
You said in your statement:

869
01:01:32.836 --> 01:01:35.586
"Each piece of tape feels different."

870
01:01:35.746 --> 01:01:38.456
"I wouldn't get it wrong."

871
01:01:39.086 --> 01:01:41.746
And:
"I was just below the open window."


872
01:01:41.916 --> 01:01:43.746
"I know what I heard."

873
01:01:43.916 --> 01:01:47.496
Then, during the reenactment,
you said something else entirely.


874
01:01:47.666 --> 01:01:49.286
How come?

875
01:01:51.996 --> 01:01:55.036
I thought
I remembered where I was, but...


876
01:01:57.536 --> 01:02:01.286
Maybe the shock of what happened next
got me mixed up.


877
01:02:01.666 --> 01:02:03.786
A psychiatrist who met with Daniel

878
01:02:03.956 --> 01:02:07.746
says emotional shock
may have altered some memories.


879
01:02:08.196 --> 01:02:09.106
Of course.

880
01:02:09.206 --> 01:02:12.036
Do you remember now
why you came back inside?


881
01:02:14.246 --> 01:02:16.246
I think I must've forgotten...

882
01:02:16.916 --> 01:02:18.536
my gloves or my phone.

883
01:02:19.416 --> 01:02:20.746
But you're not sure?

884
01:02:22.246 --> 01:02:23.996
I don't remember exactly.

885
01:02:24.166 --> 01:02:27.666
So, you went from absolute certainty
to uncertainty


886
01:02:27.836 --> 01:02:30.246
about your memories of that day.

887
01:02:30.416 --> 01:02:32.336
This is very problematic.

888
01:02:32.496 --> 01:02:35.496
You're fixating on one detail
in his memory


889
01:02:35.666 --> 01:02:38.206
to cast doubt on his whole memory.

890
01:02:38.626 --> 01:02:40.336
What do you want us to believe?

891
01:02:40.496 --> 01:02:43.836
That shock may have turned yelling
into calm voices?


892
01:02:43.996 --> 01:02:46.916
You insinuate
he lied to protect his mother.


893
01:02:47.086 --> 01:02:48.206
No.

894
01:02:48.746 --> 01:02:51.036
I'm merely signaling
the witness's doubts.


895
01:02:51.206 --> 01:02:53.456
But we are entitled to wonder.

896
01:02:53.626 --> 01:02:57.456
Daniel Maleski says he would leave
when his parents fought.


897
01:02:57.626 --> 01:03:00.836
Whereas on that day,
he happens to go out


898
01:03:00.996 --> 01:03:03.746
right when an argument
is likely to erupt.


899
01:03:03.916 --> 01:03:05.836
Thus, he doesn't hear a thing.

900
01:03:06.286 --> 01:03:08.916
I didn't happen to go out.
I fled the music.


901
01:03:09.086 --> 01:03:13.086
And he's very precise
about what he heard.


902
01:03:13.246 --> 01:03:14.916
He's never budged on that.

903
01:03:15.496 --> 01:03:18.706
The psychiatrist
and visual impairment expert


904
01:03:18.876 --> 01:03:22.126
both observed
Daniel's excellent aural memory.


905
01:03:28.286 --> 01:03:31.706
Clerk, please display

906
01:03:31.876 --> 01:03:34.376
the elements provided by Mr. Balard.

907
01:03:36.746 --> 01:03:38.286
We're listening.

908
01:03:38.456 --> 01:03:41.956
The decisive element here
is the three blood spatters


909
01:03:42.186 --> 01:03:43.516
on the woodshed,

910
01:03:43.666 --> 01:03:46.286
as indicated on the sketch.

911
01:03:47.246 --> 01:03:49.996
Can we zoom in on the woodshed?

912
01:03:51.336 --> 01:03:55.126
Their shape is typical of spatter
projected from high above.


913
01:03:55.356 --> 01:03:57.606
They are long and narrow.

914
01:03:57.806 --> 01:04:02.056
The longest measures 4 centimeters,
which is a lot.


915
01:04:02.586 --> 01:04:04.246
So, according to our tests,

916
01:04:04.416 --> 01:04:06.956
these spatters
could only have landed here


917
01:04:07.126 --> 01:04:09.666
if Mr. Maleski was struck on the head

918
01:04:09.836 --> 01:04:12.246
while on the 3rd floor balcony.

919
01:04:13.286 --> 01:04:16.336
He would have to have been
leaning over the balcony,


920
01:04:16.496 --> 01:04:20.166
his head already quite far out
when the blow was struck,


921
01:04:20.336 --> 01:04:22.916
for the spatter to land there.

922
01:04:23.146 --> 01:04:24.936
No other explanation stands.

923
01:04:25.086 --> 01:04:28.996
Did the violence of the blow
make Mr. Maleski fall?


924
01:04:29.166 --> 01:04:30.286
Most likely,

925
01:04:30.496 --> 01:04:33.916
it was the combination
of a violent blow


926
01:04:34.086 --> 01:04:36.166
and a deliberate push.

927
01:04:36.336 --> 01:04:40.126
Would you say the aggressor
was in a state of extreme anger,


928
01:04:40.336 --> 01:04:43.956
to provoke a fall after
administering such a violent blow?


929
01:04:44.166 --> 01:04:46.286
A state of rage, I'd say.

930
01:04:46.456 --> 01:04:48.086
Hard to imagine anything less.

931
01:04:48.286 --> 01:04:52.456
Such states
can increase physical strength.


932
01:05:03.786 --> 01:05:08.536
The guardrail is 1.2 meters high.

933
01:05:08.706 --> 01:05:11.746
Comes up to about here.

934
01:05:12.246 --> 01:05:14.916
Mr. Maleski was 1.82 meters tall

935
01:05:15.086 --> 01:05:17.206
and weighed 85 kilos.

936
01:05:17.536 --> 01:05:20.586
So, pushing him over that guardrail

937
01:05:20.746 --> 01:05:24.496
would have required
a very deliberate push, right?


938
01:05:24.666 --> 01:05:27.666
The entire act was very deliberate.

939
01:05:27.836 --> 01:05:29.996
Such a blow is always intentional.

940
01:05:30.206 --> 01:05:32.336
What I mean by very deliberate is...

941
01:05:32.496 --> 01:05:35.286
very coordinated. Methodical.

942
01:05:35.456 --> 01:05:37.876
Based on his weight, we can assume

943
01:05:38.036 --> 01:05:41.496
it was necessary to lift his legs
to make him fall,


944
01:05:41.666 --> 01:05:43.626
which hardly suggests rage.

945
01:05:43.786 --> 01:05:45.496
Rage does not exclude will.

946
01:05:45.666 --> 01:05:49.836
And Mr. Maleski was probably
already off-balance.


947
01:05:49.996 --> 01:05:51.586
He may have fallen

948
01:05:51.746 --> 01:05:55.166
as much from the blow
as from his own unstable position.


949
01:05:55.376 --> 01:05:58.086
As I said,
we have no material elements...


950
01:05:58.246 --> 01:06:00.376
Except those 3 drops of blood.

951
01:06:01.456 --> 01:06:06.416
Everything else must be speculated
to explain those drops, right?


952
01:06:06.586 --> 01:06:09.876
OK, but the only explanation
is the one I gave.


953
01:06:10.106 --> 01:06:13.436
You gave us a theory,
not an explanation.


954
01:06:13.586 --> 01:06:15.036
Actually, two theories.

955
01:06:15.246 --> 01:06:18.336
With and without a deliberate push.

956
01:06:19.036 --> 01:06:20.706
According to your theories,

957
01:06:20.916 --> 01:06:22.956
what type of object was used?

958
01:06:23.126 --> 01:06:25.706
A heavy object, probably in metal

959
01:06:25.916 --> 01:06:27.876
or dense wood,

960
01:06:28.036 --> 01:06:30.246
and undoubtedly with a sharp edge.

961
01:06:30.786 --> 01:06:34.336
Did you examine any such objects
found on the premises?


962
01:06:34.496 --> 01:06:37.126
You know no weapon was found.

963
01:06:37.286 --> 01:06:39.086
They're easily disposed of.

964
01:06:39.706 --> 01:06:41.246
No further questions.

965
01:06:43.416 --> 01:06:46.336
Two possible explanations
for these 3 spatters.


966
01:06:46.496 --> 01:06:50.626
Either they came from here,
after a violent blow.


967
01:06:51.166 --> 01:06:54.036
Or they resulted when the skull

968
01:06:54.206 --> 01:06:55.876
hit this roof ledge,

969
01:06:56.086 --> 01:06:57.496
approximately here.

970
01:06:57.836 --> 01:06:59.666
The first hypothesis is unlikely.

971
01:06:59.836 --> 01:07:04.286
It's inconsistent with the shape
and movement of the spatters.


972
01:07:05.266 --> 01:07:07.056
Focusing on the second hypothesis,

973
01:07:07.206 --> 01:07:10.956
we must take into account
the bounce caused by the impact


974
01:07:11.126 --> 01:07:12.456
on the roof ledge.

975
01:07:13.286 --> 01:07:16.456
I'll show you a video
of our in-situ tests.


976
01:07:21.976 --> 01:07:22.886
There.

977
01:07:22.956 --> 01:07:26.706
As you can see
in our reenactment with a dummy,


978
01:07:26.936 --> 01:07:30.056
such an impact
causes the body to turn abruptly.


979
01:07:30.206 --> 01:07:33.666
And during that rollover, or spin,

980
01:07:34.036 --> 01:07:36.166
a fraction of a second after impact,

981
01:07:36.336 --> 01:07:40.206
these 3 spatters are projected

982
01:07:40.436 --> 01:07:41.886
onto this surface.

983
01:07:45.496 --> 01:07:47.286
The only valid explanation

984
01:07:47.456 --> 01:07:50.996
is that Mr. Maleski
fell from the attic window.


985
01:07:51.166 --> 01:07:52.456
I believe it's the only way

986
01:07:52.666 --> 01:07:54.956
he could've bounced off the roof,

987
01:07:55.436 --> 01:07:57.016
and sustained such an injury.

988
01:07:57.166 --> 01:07:59.536
You use the cautious qualifier
"I believe".


989
01:07:59.706 --> 01:08:00.996
So it's your opinion.

990
01:08:01.586 --> 01:08:04.336
How do you explain
the lack of DNA or trace tissue


991
01:08:04.536 --> 01:08:07.916
at the point of impact,
or "bounce" as you call it?


992
01:08:08.416 --> 01:08:09.996
I'll show you.

993
01:08:10.166 --> 01:08:12.286
This is a test we carried out

994
01:08:12.516 --> 01:08:14.596
under comparable conditions.

995
01:08:14.746 --> 01:08:17.916
At the time of the incident,
there was a layer of ice


996
01:08:18.086 --> 01:08:20.746
underneath a thick layer of snow.

997
01:08:21.956 --> 01:08:25.126
We see the snow melting
in acceleration.


998
01:08:25.286 --> 01:08:26.626
And we can see,

999
01:08:26.786 --> 01:08:30.706
during 1 hour and 50 minutes,
that the runoff


1000
01:08:31.206 --> 01:08:34.836
takes with it all residue
embedded at the point of impact.


1001
01:08:34.916 --> 01:08:36.706
It ends up with the blood
that was already


1002
01:08:36.806 --> 01:08:37.886
down here.

1003
01:08:38.036 --> 01:08:41.666
You call the violent blow hypothesis
