1496
01:36:36.706 --> 01:36:39.536
He's told me countless times
how hard you are.


1497
01:36:39.706 --> 01:36:41.746
He's telling you
what you want to hear.


1498
01:36:41.916 --> 01:36:44.876
He can feel your guilt
and he's trying to reassure you,


1499
01:36:45.106 --> 01:36:46.476
don't you see that?

1500
01:36:46.626 --> 01:36:49.126
You've never stopped
feeling guilty about him!


1501
01:36:49.356 --> 01:36:50.606
You're cold-hearted.

1502
01:36:50.746 --> 01:36:51.836
You have no pity.

1503
01:36:51.996 --> 01:36:53.666
And you have
way too much for yourself.


1504
01:36:53.836 --> 01:36:56.746
I can't stand any more
of your fucking ice!


1505
01:36:59.206 --> 01:37:00.836
- You're violent!
- Yes, I am!


1506
01:37:29.626 --> 01:37:30.876
So...

1507
01:37:31.416 --> 01:37:34.996
Can you tell us
where you found this recording?


1508
01:37:36.916 --> 01:37:39.586
On a USB key belonging to the victim.

1509
01:37:39.746 --> 01:37:43.996
He made several dozen recordings
on his cellphone.


1510
01:37:44.746 --> 01:37:48.626
For 6 months, he'd been recording
moments from, his life.


1511
01:37:48.786 --> 01:37:50.666
For a literary project, apparently.

1512
01:37:50.876 --> 01:37:53.036
Did he transcribe all the recordings?

1513
01:37:53.206 --> 01:37:55.246
Yes, except this last argument.

1514
01:37:56.036 --> 01:37:59.626
Does your investigation link
this argument to his death?


1515
01:37:59.786 --> 01:38:03.416
Yes. They occurred 20 hours apart
and have common themes.


1516
01:38:03.586 --> 01:38:05.456
He criticizes her infidelity.

1517
01:38:05.626 --> 01:38:08.036
A pretty girl comes the next day.

1518
01:38:08.376 --> 01:38:10.786
A literature student,

1519
01:38:10.956 --> 01:38:13.916
to interview Sandra Voyter
about her books.


1520
01:38:14.706 --> 01:38:17.206
There must've been
tension in the air.


1521
01:38:17.376 --> 01:38:18.586
The two women

1522
01:38:18.786 --> 01:38:22.876
were enjoying themselves
while he worked hard upstairs.


1523
01:38:24.246 --> 01:38:28.086
The argument can be seen as
a dress rehearsal for the next day.


1524
01:38:28.246 --> 01:38:32.626
How do you interpret
the violent outbursts?


1525
01:38:33.086 --> 01:38:34.626
We hear blows.

1526
01:38:35.416 --> 01:38:38.666
A physical altercation,
the accused striking her husband.


1527
01:38:38.836 --> 01:38:42.456
What makes it possible for you
to reach that conclusion?


1528
01:38:43.336 --> 01:38:46.086
She seems to be
in a more intense state of rage.


1529
01:38:49.206 --> 01:38:51.956
- Sorry?
- Speak directly to the court.


1530
01:38:52.126 --> 01:38:55.496
She's clearly
in a more intense state of rage.


1531
01:38:56.996 --> 01:39:01.586
Her shouts at the end of the audio
are the last step


1532
01:39:01.746 --> 01:39:04.166
before the violence gets physical.

1533
01:39:04.586 --> 01:39:08.086
The confusion that follows
is hard to analyze, but...


1534
01:39:08.496 --> 01:39:11.626
we hear blows to
a body or a face,

1535
01:39:11.786 --> 01:39:14.456
and the muffled screams we hear

1536
01:39:14.626 --> 01:39:16.286
are Mr. Maleski's.

1537
01:39:16.456 --> 01:39:18.666
You mentioned
bruises on Mrs Voyter.


1538
01:39:18.836 --> 01:39:21.036
Show Exhibit 9, please.

1539
01:39:21.786 --> 01:39:25.126
This photo was taken
on the day her husband died.


1540
01:39:25.456 --> 01:39:26.876
How did she explain it?

1541
01:39:27.036 --> 01:39:30.746
She initially told us
she'd bumped into a kitchen counter.


1542
01:39:31.376 --> 01:39:34.456
We pointed out that the bruising
was around her wrist,


1543
01:39:34.666 --> 01:39:37.706
and looked a lot
like signs of a struggle.


1544
01:39:38.416 --> 01:39:41.036
Later, when we played her
the recording,


1545
01:39:41.206 --> 01:39:43.786
she admitted it had happened then,

1546
01:39:44.286 --> 01:39:45.956
during their brief struggle.

1547
01:39:46.126 --> 01:39:48.036
So you admit you lied?

1548
01:39:48.956 --> 01:39:50.086
Yes.

1549
01:39:50.706 --> 01:39:51.956
Because..

1550
01:39:52.286 --> 01:39:56.206
I was afraid
that if I mentioned it,


1551
01:39:57.126 --> 01:40:00.086
I knew it would make me a suspect
and I got scared.


1552
01:40:00.246 --> 01:40:03.166
And you didn't know
he'd recorded the fight.


1553
01:40:03.336 --> 01:40:04.666
So you lied twice.

1554
01:40:04.836 --> 01:40:08.376
About the bruises,
and by not mentioning the fight.


1555
01:40:08.536 --> 01:40:11.206
For me, it was just one lie.

1556
01:40:11.376 --> 01:40:15.536
Because, if I'd been honest about the
bruises, I'd have mentioned the argument.


1557
01:40:15.956 --> 01:40:18.376
I didn't want to be seen as guilty.

1558
01:40:18.586 --> 01:40:20.456
As no guilty person ever does.

1559
01:40:20.626 --> 01:40:23.036
Can we time the bruises exactly?

1560
01:40:23.206 --> 01:40:25.536
The doctor examined her
the following day.


1561
01:40:26.336 --> 01:40:30.586
It was too late to determine exactly
when they occurred.


1562
01:40:30.786 --> 01:40:32.336
So it's possible

1563
01:40:32.496 --> 01:40:36.416
a second fight caused the bruises
on the day Mr. Maleski died.


1564
01:40:45.786 --> 01:40:48.786
What do we hear
at the end of the argument?


1565
01:40:49.536 --> 01:40:51.786
The first sound of breaking glass

1566
01:40:51.956 --> 01:40:54.416
is me throwing a glass
against the wall.


1567
01:40:54.586 --> 01:40:57.126
A wine glass that was on the table.

1568
01:40:57.916 --> 01:41:02.376
After that, I went over to my husband
and I slapped him.


1569
01:41:02.996 --> 01:41:06.206
That's when he grabbed my wrist,
quite violently.


1570
01:41:06.376 --> 01:41:08.536
That's the struggling we can hear.

1571
01:41:09.126 --> 01:41:13.496
Just after, I tried to stop him from
throwing picture frames to the floor


1572
01:41:13.666 --> 01:41:15.706
but I couldn't,
so we hear them shattering.


1573
01:41:16.416 --> 01:41:18.536
Aside from that slap,
did you hit him?


1574
01:41:19.086 --> 01:41:20.206
No.

1575
01:41:21.536 --> 01:41:22.876
What we hear next

1576
01:41:23.036 --> 01:41:27.416
is Samuel repeatedly hitting himself
in the face and the head,


1577
01:41:28.086 --> 01:41:30.586
and then punching the wall.

1578
01:41:30.746 --> 01:41:32.586
You can still see the dent.

1579
01:41:33.376 --> 01:41:37.336
There are a few around the house,
it's not the first time he did that.


1580
01:41:37.876 --> 01:41:41.166
Years ago, he already broke a finger

1581
01:41:41.666 --> 01:41:44.036
punching the wall during an episode.

1582
01:41:46.086 --> 01:41:48.496
We have photos
of those dents in the wall.


1583
01:41:48.666 --> 01:41:49.666
Thank you.

1584
01:41:49.856 --> 01:41:50.606
Here.

1585
01:41:50.746 --> 01:41:52.996
And the X-ray
of his fractured finger,


1586
01:41:53.206 --> 01:41:56.836
taken in June 2017
at the hospital in Grenoble.


1587
01:41:58.066 --> 01:41:59.356
Is it fair to say

1588
01:41:59.496 --> 01:42:04.336
your depiction of the violence
is interpretive and not objective?


1589
01:42:06.126 --> 01:42:08.786
She repeatedly lied to us,
so believing her...


1590
01:42:08.996 --> 01:42:10.836
Thus, this is about believing,

1591
01:42:10.996 --> 01:42:12.376
or not believing.

1592
01:42:12.706 --> 01:42:14.586
It's a subjective opinion,

1593
01:42:14.746 --> 01:42:16.996
based on an ambiguous recording.

1594
01:42:17.956 --> 01:42:20.836
You link the argument
of the day of the death.


1595
01:42:20.996 --> 01:42:23.706
You call it a "dress rehearsal".

1596
01:42:23.876 --> 01:42:25.666
Do you have any direct proof?

1597
01:42:25.836 --> 01:42:28.876
The recording
is direct proof of a fight.


1598
01:42:29.036 --> 01:42:30.836
I mean the day of the death.

1599
01:42:31.996 --> 01:42:35.246
With no witnesses or confessions,
we must interpret.


1600
01:42:37.876 --> 01:42:40.996
In fact, this violent fight is...

1601
01:42:41.166 --> 01:42:44.246
phantasmal.
It exists only as fantasy.


1602
01:42:44.876 --> 01:42:46.336
You float the idea,

1603
01:42:46.496 --> 01:42:48.166
the prosecutor floats it,

1604
01:42:48.336 --> 01:42:51.126
over or around the facts,

1605
01:42:51.286 --> 01:42:54.626
making it omnipresent
here in court, but...


1606
01:42:56.456 --> 01:42:59.626
We risk turning this fantasy
into a reality


1607
01:42:59.786 --> 01:43:03.126
simply because
there was indeed a fight


1608
01:43:03.496 --> 01:43:06.206
the day before Mr. Maleski died.

1609
01:43:06.746 --> 01:43:10.626
Don't substitute the day before
for the next day.


1610
01:43:11.836 --> 01:43:15.496
We can't fill the blanks
with a supposition,


1611
01:43:15.666 --> 01:43:19.416
simply because we have sounds
for one and not the other.


1612
01:43:19.586 --> 01:43:20.586
Mrs Voyter,

1613
01:43:20.666 --> 01:43:24.456
did you know he'd recorded
you before you were told?


1614
01:43:26.166 --> 01:43:29.746
No, but I knew that he often recorded
moments of our lives.


1615
01:43:29.956 --> 01:43:32.246
He didn't always let you know?

1616
01:43:32.416 --> 01:43:34.666
What were these recordings?

1617
01:43:35.746 --> 01:43:37.626
At first, he would mention it.

1618
01:43:37.786 --> 01:43:40.456
After a while,
he did it without us knowing.


1619
01:43:40.626 --> 01:43:43.336
He recorded conversations,

1620
01:43:43.496 --> 01:43:45.496
Daniel's piano lessons,

1621
01:43:45.666 --> 01:43:49.246
and sometimes just himself,
talking to himself.


1622
01:43:49.416 --> 01:43:53.996
I think he wanted to gather material
to help him start writing again.


1623
01:43:55.206 --> 01:43:58.536
Now, with hindsight,
it seems possible


1624
01:43:58.706 --> 01:44:01.996
that he could have provoked
this fight just to record it.


1625
01:44:02.336 --> 01:44:06.536
Wait, are you implying
you're the victim of a twisted man?


1626
01:44:06.706 --> 01:44:07.876
Seriously?

1627
01:44:08.416 --> 01:44:11.836
He recorded her in secret.
It's a valid question.


1628
01:44:11.996 --> 01:44:14.586
You forget the situation is perverse.

1629
01:44:15.416 --> 01:44:16.706
Now the victim is on trial!

1630
01:44:16.876 --> 01:44:18.786
No, but my client has a point.

1631
01:44:18.956 --> 01:44:22.246
Can you explain
what he means by cheating,


1632
01:44:22.416 --> 01:44:23.746
and how he found out?

1633
01:44:26.086 --> 01:44:29.086
He went through my phone
and discovered messages


1634
01:44:29.246 --> 01:44:31.956
from a woman I'd met
at the beginning of that year.


1635
01:44:32.126 --> 01:44:34.336
What do you mean by "met"?

1636
01:44:34.746 --> 01:44:37.086
It was sexual,
we slept together twice.


1637
01:44:37.246 --> 01:44:38.246
Twice?

1638
01:44:38.286 --> 01:44:39.286
Yes.

1639
01:44:39.456 --> 01:44:42.086
On the recording you said once.

1640
01:44:42.996 --> 01:44:45.336
It meant with just one person.

1641
01:44:46.036 --> 01:44:47.336
Hang on...

1642
01:44:47.836 --> 01:44:51.336
Samuel mentions
numerous affairs in the past.


1643
01:44:51.496 --> 01:44:54.166
It sounds like
you cheated constantly.


1644
01:44:54.376 --> 01:44:55.996
That's not true.

1645
01:44:56.536 --> 01:45:00.086
I had a few flings
the year of Daniel's accident.


1646
01:45:00.246 --> 01:45:02.496
It wasn't cheating,
because Samuel knew.


1647
01:45:02.666 --> 01:45:04.206
He found out each time?

1648
01:45:04.536 --> 01:45:06.086
No, I told him.

1649
01:45:06.746 --> 01:45:08.336
It was a tricky year.

1650
01:45:08.496 --> 01:45:10.746
You want us to believe
he agreed to it?


1651
01:45:11.376 --> 01:45:15.336
I'm not saying that,
I'm saying I was honest about it.


1652
01:45:16.086 --> 01:45:17.786
Interesting take on honesty.

1653
01:45:17.956 --> 01:45:21.246
But the year he died
you quit being honest, why?


1654
01:45:24.416 --> 01:45:25.916
Things were different.

1655
01:45:26.086 --> 01:45:29.536
I felt that it would hurt him
too much at that time.


1656
01:45:29.706 --> 01:45:32.626
Because you had feelings
for that woman?


1657
01:45:32.786 --> 01:45:35.626
No, I felt it would hurt him
because he was fragile.


1658
01:45:35.786 --> 01:45:37.286
And...

1659
01:45:37.456 --> 01:45:40.416
As I said,
with her it was just sexual.


1660
01:45:40.586 --> 01:45:43.376
The person I had feelings for
was Samuel.


1661
01:45:43.536 --> 01:45:45.416
Interesting take on feelings.

1662
01:45:45.586 --> 01:45:46.916
I'm trying to understand.

1663
01:45:47.086 --> 01:45:50.286
At first you agreed
on an open relationship,


1664
01:45:50.456 --> 01:45:52.166
then that changed?

1665
01:45:53.336 --> 01:45:56.246
I don't even know
what that means, I'm sorry.


1666
01:45:56.416 --> 01:45:59.876
Sorry. No, we never had
that kind of agreement.


1667
01:46:00.036 --> 01:46:04.376
After the accident,
we were both trying to feel better.


1668
01:46:04.536 --> 01:46:06.706
I needed that to keep it together,

1669
01:46:06.916 --> 01:46:08.086
and I was honest.

1670
01:46:08.246 --> 01:46:11.586
But then you quit being honest,
and he held you accountable.


1671
01:46:11.746 --> 01:46:14.166
He doesn't sound "fragile".

1672
01:46:14.336 --> 01:46:16.706
- Do you admit he was jealous?
- Yes.


1673
01:46:16.876 --> 01:46:18.786
OK. Had he become obsessed?

1674
01:46:18.996 --> 01:46:20.666
No. I don't know...

1675
01:46:21.086 --> 01:46:23.206
He was hurt, that's true.

1676
01:46:24.626 --> 01:46:26.876
Sometimes when we fought
he brought it up.


1677
01:46:27.036 --> 01:46:29.536
But he didn't think about it
all the time.


1678
01:46:30.036 --> 01:46:34.086
According to your logic,
all Samuel's problems were my fault.


1679
01:46:34.246 --> 01:46:37.086
That's not true.
His pain came from a deeper place.


1680
01:46:37.286 --> 01:46:41.496
According to "his" logic
you're to blame, as we heard.


1681
01:46:41.666 --> 01:46:45.036
What does he mean when he says
his work was plundered?


1682
01:46:45.246 --> 01:46:48.336
No, there wasn't any plundering.

1683
01:46:48.496 --> 01:46:52.706
In the book that he abandoned,
there was an interesting passage...


1684
01:46:52.876 --> 01:46:54.666
A passage?
How many pages?


1685
01:46:54.996 --> 01:46:56.036
About 20.

1686
01:46:56.246 --> 01:46:57.376
27.

1687
01:46:58.166 --> 01:47:01.536
It was just a rough outline.
I thought the idea was brilliant.


1688
01:47:01.706 --> 01:47:02.836
Can you summarize it?

1689
01:47:02.996 --> 01:47:05.586
Must we enter into a literary debate?

1690
01:47:05.746 --> 01:47:07.746
This isn't literary, it's concrete.

1691
01:47:07.956 --> 01:47:09.706
It's the heart of their conflict.

1692
01:47:10.036 --> 01:47:13.286
I don't know how else
to present it to the jurors.


1693
01:47:13.456 --> 01:47:14.456
Nor do I.

1694
01:47:14.586 --> 01:47:15.626
Proceed.

1695
01:47:15.786 --> 01:47:16.956
Well...

1696
01:47:17.126 --> 01:47:20.126
It was about a guy imagining
how his life would've been


1697
01:47:20.286 --> 01:47:22.666
without the accident
that killed his brother.


1698
01:47:22.996 --> 01:47:25.836
He wakes up and finds himself
in two different realities.


1699
01:47:25.996 --> 01:47:27.996
In one, the accident
is the center of his life.


1700
01:47:28.166 --> 01:47:30.206
In the other, it never happened.

1701
01:47:30.376 --> 01:47:32.836
I told Samuel I loved it.

1702
01:47:32.996 --> 01:47:36.126
He had me read
everything he wrote back then.


1703
01:47:36.456 --> 01:47:39.706
Soon after,
he abandoned the whole book.


1704
01:47:39.876 --> 01:47:42.626
I asked him if I could use the idea
and he said yes.


1705
01:47:42.836 --> 01:47:43.876
No.

1706
01:47:44.536 --> 01:47:47.206
He couldn't have,
he calls it plundering.


1707
01:47:47.376 --> 01:47:49.206
It's an argument.

1708
01:47:49.376 --> 01:47:52.626
People exaggerate and alter facts
when they argue.


1709
01:47:52.786 --> 01:47:55.586
It's no exaggeration to say his
book became yours: "ECLIPSE".


1710
01:47:59.916 --> 01:48:03.626
All I took was this idea.

1711
01:48:03.786 --> 01:48:06.376
My characters are a woman
and her daughter,


1712
01:48:06.536 --> 01:48:07.706
and I developed the story

1713
01:48:07.916 --> 01:48:09.746
over 300 pages.

1714
01:48:11.876 --> 01:48:16.126
I can't believe I must tell you what's the
difference between an outline and a novel?


1715
01:48:16.286 --> 01:48:17.626
He agreed to it.

1716
01:48:17.786 --> 01:48:21.996
And when he read it, he said
I did something very different.


1717
01:48:22.166 --> 01:48:25.916
Sometimes yes, when we argued
it came out, because...


1718
01:48:26.086 --> 01:48:28.836
he was upset
because he couldn't write.


1719
01:48:29.036 --> 01:48:32.786
The only thing we know for sure
is that "it came out".


1720
01:48:32.956 --> 01:48:34.666
Did the two of you...

1721
01:48:35.246 --> 01:48:38.206
argue again
before the time of his death?


1722
01:48:38.376 --> 01:48:40.456
It must've been very tense.

1723
01:48:43.166 --> 01:48:44.246
We were...

1724
01:48:45.496 --> 01:48:47.246
we were both really shaken.

1725
01:48:47.416 --> 01:48:50.836
We were both keeping to ourselves
and Samuel was...


1726
01:48:52.086 --> 01:48:53.626
I don't know, something was gone.

1727
01:48:53.786 --> 01:48:56.586
He was depleted,
his energy was just gone.


1728
01:48:56.746 --> 01:49:00.166
In the audio, I hear Samuel Maleski
arguing strenuously.


1729
01:49:00.336 --> 01:49:03.626
I hear a man determined
to regain control of his life.


1730
01:49:03.786 --> 01:49:06.746
In no way
a man who has decided to give up.


1731
01:49:06.916 --> 01:49:11.456
Samuel's psychiatrist said he was
combative in their last sessions.


1732
01:49:11.626 --> 01:49:16.246
Do you kill yourself after fighting
for time and self-esteem?


1733
01:49:16.416 --> 01:49:20.956
Do you kill yourself after pleading
so fiercely and energetically


1734
01:49:21.126 --> 01:49:24.626
for balance and justice
in your relationship? No.


1735
01:49:25.626 --> 01:49:28.416
That's the main flaw
in the suicide theory.


1736
01:49:28.586 --> 01:49:31.786
You say he seemed "depleted".

1737
01:49:31.956 --> 01:49:33.536
His energy was gone.

1738
01:49:33.876 --> 01:49:37.876
May I read from one of Mrs Voyter's
recent books, "The Black House"?


1739
01:49:38.036 --> 01:49:39.876
We judge facts, not books.

1740
01:49:40.036 --> 01:49:42.746
Judge, this is a slippery slope.

1741
01:49:42.916 --> 01:49:46.336
In 2017, Sandra Voyter herself
declared, and I quote,


1742
01:49:46.496 --> 01:49:49.536
"My books are linked to my life
and those in it."


1743
01:49:49.746 --> 01:49:52.666
Objection! She's always said
her work is fiction.


1744
01:49:53.286 --> 01:49:55.746
First book is her mother's death!

1745
01:49:55.916 --> 01:49:57.666
Second, a rift with her father.

1746
01:49:57.836 --> 01:50:00.036
Third, her son's accident, etc.

1747
01:50:00.206 --> 01:50:02.286
Her books are part of this trial.

1748
01:50:02.456 --> 01:50:05.336
Her life is in them,
her relationship in particular.


1749
01:50:05.496 --> 01:50:07.336
Go ahead, but keep it brief.

1750
01:50:07.996 --> 01:50:11.126
This is a wife
talking about her husband.


1751
01:50:13.956 --> 01:50:16.916
"He'd stopped complaining.
He'd given up."


1752
01:50:17.416 --> 01:50:20.706
"She studied him,
repulsed by his resignation."


1753
01:50:21.416 --> 01:50:24.626
"An idea sprouted in her mind,
a seed of deliverance."


1754
01:50:24.956 --> 01:50:26.376
"The possibility of his death."

1755
01:50:26.536 --> 01:50:27.626
Give us the context.

1756
01:50:27.786 --> 01:50:29.626
Later: "How does one kill?"

1757
01:50:29.786 --> 01:50:32.586
"What about the body? Its weight?

1758
01:50:32.746 --> 01:50:35.036
"She could think of nothing else.

1759
01:50:35.456 --> 01:50:39.206
"She saw him dead,
his body a lump no longer desired.


1760
01:50:39.376 --> 01:50:41.206
"The body she'd loved

1761
01:50:41.376 --> 01:50:43.586
was now in the way
and had to go."


1762
01:50:43.746 --> 01:50:45.456
I'll provide the context.

1763
01:50:45.666 --> 01:50:49.126
This is a minor character,
going insane,


1764
01:50:49.286 --> 01:50:51.286
who doesn't act on her thoughts.

1765
01:50:51.456 --> 01:50:53.876
A novel is not life!
An author is not her characters.


1766
01:50:54.036 --> 01:50:57.336
But an author can express herself
through her characters.


1767
01:50:57.496 --> 01:50:58.956
You flagged this passage.

1768
01:50:59.126 --> 01:51:00.916
How can we not see a link?

1769
01:51:01.126 --> 01:51:03.126
Is Stephen King a serial killer?

1770
01:51:03.286 --> 01:51:06.286
Did his wife turn up dead
in suspicious circumstances?


1771
01:51:06.456 --> 01:51:07.536
Focus on the facts!

1772
01:51:07.746 --> 01:51:11.126
Mr. Renzi,
I strongly advise you to calm down.


1773
01:51:11.286 --> 01:51:14.536
Prosecutor, I advise you
to follow Mr. Renzi's advice.


1774
01:51:15.206 --> 01:51:17.376
Focus on the facts.

1775
01:51:20.626 --> 01:51:22.206
Aside from the slap

1776
01:51:22.416 --> 01:51:25.166
you admitted to,
did you ever hit your husband?


1777
01:51:25.626 --> 01:51:26.706
Never?

1778
01:51:27.336 --> 01:51:28.586
That was the only time?

1779
01:51:28.786 --> 01:51:32.166
You were always a good,
admirable soul,


1780
01:51:32.626 --> 01:51:34.416
altruistic, reasonable,

1781
01:51:34.586 --> 01:51:36.706
trying to save him from himself,

1782
01:51:36.876 --> 01:51:39.416
except on this recording?
Rotten luck!


1783
01:51:40.996 --> 01:51:42.996
Any more questions
for the witness?


1784
01:51:43.166 --> 01:51:45.286
I have one more, if I may.

1785
01:51:46.586 --> 01:51:49.086
I'd like to know if Maleski

1786
01:51:49.286 --> 01:51:51.376
sent the transcripts to anyone?

1787
01:51:51.536 --> 01:51:54.086
He sent them to a publisher friend,
Paul Nachez,


1788
01:51:54.246 --> 01:51:56.206
slated to publish his first novel.

1789
01:51:56.376 --> 01:51:58.036
Email from August 9, 2017:

1790
01:51:58.206 --> 01:52:01.746
"I'm writing again, I need your eye.
Still rough, eager to talk."


1791
01:52:01.916 --> 01:52:03.086
Nachez's response:

1792
01:52:03.286 --> 01:52:05.626
"Sure, send it and I'll read it."

1793
01:52:05.786 --> 01:52:08.746
Up to his death,
Maleski sent 4 texts a week.


1794
01:52:08.916 --> 01:52:10.746
What was their communication like?

1795
01:52:10.916 --> 01:52:13.086
The publisher never replied.

1796
01:52:13.416 --> 01:52:16.126
Apparently he was busy
and the project mystified him.


1797
01:52:16.836 --> 01:52:18.416
His friend's silence

1798
01:52:18.626 --> 01:52:22.836
must've hurt Mr. Maleski's
already low self-esteem.


1799
01:52:22.996 --> 01:52:24.536
He feels rejected.

1800
01:52:25.036 --> 01:52:27.786
When we read all the writing he sent,

1801
01:52:27.956 --> 01:52:30.246
it's difficult
to identify a storyline.


1802
01:52:30.416 --> 01:52:31.996
At best, it's a project.

1803
01:52:32.166 --> 01:52:33.666
Maleski is a "project man".

1804
01:52:33.836 --> 01:52:36.336
His first abandoned novel,
the chalet...


1805
01:52:37.036 --> 01:52:40.996
So, since we're being asked
to mix justice and literature,


1806
01:52:41.166 --> 01:52:43.036
to imagine what we don't know,

1807
01:52:43.206 --> 01:52:46.996
let's imagine
Samuel Maleski's final year.


1808
01:52:47.166 --> 01:52:48.916
And I'm dabbling in fantasy?

1809
01:52:49.126 --> 01:52:53.036
Give me half the time
you took to read a book!


1810
01:52:53.206 --> 01:52:54.586
Get to the point.

1811
01:52:55.166 --> 01:52:57.376
What was
Samuel Maleski's final year like?


1812
01:52:58.786 --> 01:53:02.956
After accumulating debt
from medical procedures in London,


1813
01:53:03.126 --> 01:53:06.166
he insists on returning
to his hometown.


1814
01:53:06.336 --> 01:53:09.916
He finds a chalet to fix up and rent.
They'll pay off their debts.


1815
01:53:10.086 --> 01:53:13.036
He'll quit teaching
and start writing full-time.


1816
01:53:13.456 --> 01:53:17.166
Renovation proves tricky.
They have to take out a loan.


1817
01:53:17.956 --> 01:53:19.956
A vicious circle begins.

1818
01:53:20.126 --> 01:53:24.126
Samuel needs his teaching wages.
Renovations drag on.


1819
01:53:24.286 --> 01:53:26.456
A year and a half later,

1820
01:53:26.626 --> 01:53:27.996
he feels trapped.

1821
01:53:28.336 --> 01:53:29.876
He's a wounded man.

1822
01:53:30.086 --> 01:53:31.876
His son's accident,
his abandoned novel,


1823
01:53:32.036 --> 01:53:34.416
his wife publishing book after book.

1824
01:53:35.166 --> 01:53:36.586
He must write!

1825
01:53:38.916 --> 01:53:42.246
He quits the antidepressants
and starts recording his life,


1826
01:53:42.416 --> 01:53:44.996
embarking on a kind of auto-fiction,

1827
01:53:45.166 --> 01:53:48.206
perhaps inspired by Sandra's method.

1828
01:53:48.376 --> 01:53:51.286
And why not?
She borrows from their lives.


1829
01:53:51.456 --> 01:53:53.376
She did borrow his idea.

1830
01:53:53.586 --> 01:53:54.876
Save it for your plea.

1831
01:53:55.036 --> 01:53:58.956
He's running.
But refuses to see that transcribing


1832
01:53:59.166 --> 01:54:00.246
is not writing.

1833
01:54:00.416 --> 01:54:03.086
His publisher friend's silence
humiliates him.


1834
01:54:04.286 --> 01:54:07.246
What do we hear
in the March 4th fight?


1835
01:54:07.586 --> 01:54:10.536
The energy, the willfulness...
What is it?


1836
01:54:10.916 --> 01:54:12.496
The energy of despair.

1837
01:54:12.666 --> 01:54:15.496
The final push before giving up.

1838
01:54:18.786 --> 01:54:23.036
In his final days, this man
isn't facing a war in his marriage.


1839
01:54:24.246 --> 01:54:26.336
He's facing his own failures.

1840
01:54:28.036 --> 01:54:30.166
Sandra Voyter is only guilty

1841
01:54:30.336 --> 01:54:32.996
of succeeding
where her husband failed.


1842
01:54:37.036 --> 01:54:41.456
Despite appearances, those were not
Mr. Renzi's closing arguments.


1843
01:54:43.206 --> 01:54:44.956
That wasn't Samuel.

1844
01:54:45.126 --> 01:54:48.246
It's Friday evening,
we have a weekend ahead of us.


1845
01:54:48.916 --> 01:54:51.456
Before I adjourn,
I have an announcement.


1846
01:54:51.626 --> 01:54:54.956
I've decided to call Daniel
back to the bar on Monday.


1847
01:54:55.376 --> 01:54:57.626
He has new information of interest.

1848
01:54:57.836 --> 01:55:01.376
Since the witness
is the defendant's son


1849
01:55:01.836 --> 01:55:03.746
and lives with his mother,

1850
01:55:03.916 --> 01:55:07.416
I'm asking everyone
to refrain from contacting him.


1851
01:55:07.876 --> 01:55:11.286
Obviously, if contact is inevitable,

1852
01:55:11.456 --> 01:55:14.376
refrain from discussing the trial.

1853
01:55:14.536 --> 01:55:15.786
Mrs Berger,

1854
01:55:15.956 --> 01:55:19.036
you'll stay with Daniel all weekend.

1855
01:55:20.036 --> 01:55:23.416
See to it these rules are respected.

1856
01:55:23.626 --> 01:55:25.496
I insist that no one,

1857
01:55:25.666 --> 01:55:29.956
absolutely no one,
can ask him about his testimony.


1858
01:55:30.836 --> 01:55:33.036
Have a good weekend,
get some rest.


1859
01:55:33.206 --> 01:55:34.916
Court is adjourned.

1860
01:56:22.956 --> 01:56:25.166
- Come get warm.
- Ready in 10!


1861
01:56:31.456 --> 01:56:32.586
You OK?

1862
01:56:39.916 --> 01:56:41.996
I think I want to be alone.

1863
01:56:43.456 --> 01:56:44.666
OK.

1864
01:56:46.336 --> 01:56:48.626
- You can eat in your room.
- No.


1865
01:56:48.786 --> 01:56:50.666
I want to be alone this weekend.

1866
01:56:51.166 --> 01:56:52.286
Before I testify.

1867
01:56:52.456 --> 01:56:53.456
Alone?

1868
01:56:53.536 --> 01:56:55.166
Just you and me?

1869
01:56:56.166 --> 01:56:57.166
Is that it?

1870
01:56:58.786 --> 01:57:00.416
Are you sure?

1871
01:57:01.626 --> 01:57:04.876
We can find other solutions.
It's a big house.


1872
01:57:05.496 --> 01:57:07.036
I want her to leave.

1873
01:57:17.956 --> 01:57:19.536
I just spoke to Daniel.

1874
01:57:20.586 --> 01:57:23.246
He wants to be alone this weekend.

1875
01:57:23.416 --> 01:57:25.126
Until the end of the trial.

1876
01:57:39.586 --> 01:57:41.836
Is that what you want?

1877
01:57:46.786 --> 01:57:49.286
OK. Is it because
of what you heard today?


1878
01:57:49.456 --> 01:57:52.706
I couldn't talk to you
about all that before.


1879
01:57:52.876 --> 01:57:55.166
We weren't allowed to..

1880
01:57:56.416 --> 01:57:57.536
No trial talk.

1881
01:57:57.706 --> 01:58:00.416
I know, I'm just talking to my son.

1882
01:58:00.876 --> 01:58:01.956
OK.

1883
01:58:03.246 --> 01:58:05.786
I totally understand
that you need calm.


1884
01:58:05.956 --> 01:58:08.376
I can mind my own business,
keep to myself.


1885
01:58:08.536 --> 01:58:11.786
I won't talk to you
if you don't want. Can we try that?


1886
01:58:11.996 --> 01:58:13.206
No speaking English.

1887
01:58:14.246 --> 01:58:16.336
You can talk to me.

1888
01:58:17.376 --> 01:58:21.536
Couldn't you and I discuss this,
and then you decide?


1889
01:58:23.706 --> 01:58:25.746
I think he's made his decision.

1890
01:58:36.706 --> 01:58:38.916
Yeah, I'll just get my stuff.

1891
01:59:05.286 --> 01:59:06.876
Somebody said,

1892
01:59:07.706 --> 01:59:10.086
of course money
doesn't make you happy,


1893
01:59:10.416 --> 01:59:14.456
but it's still better to cry in a car
than in a subway.


1894
01:59:17.876 --> 01:59:18.916
Who said that?

1895
01:59:19.086 --> 01:59:20.416
I don't know.

1896
02:00:21.626 --> 02:00:22.916
Sorry.

1897
02:00:48.456 --> 02:00:49.536
Go on.

1898
02:00:56.376 --> 02:00:57.666
Eat up.

1899
02:01:26.876 --> 02:01:27.996
Snoop...

1900
02:01:40.246 --> 02:01:41.416
Marge!

1901
02:01:43.836 --> 02:01:46.126
Marge, come quick, please!

1902
02:01:52.706 --> 02:01:53.706
What is it?

1903
02:01:56.586 --> 02:01:59.086
I gave him aspirin,
I messed up bad.


1904
02:02:00.166 --> 02:02:02.206
- You gave him aspirin?
- Yes!


1905
02:02:02.376 --> 02:02:03.496
How much?

1906
02:02:04.086 --> 02:02:06.456
8 or 10, I can't remember.

1907
02:02:06.626 --> 02:02:07.626
A lot.

1908
02:02:08.456 --> 02:02:09.876
Make him vomit.

1909
02:02:10.036 --> 02:02:11.206
Why'd you do that?

1910
02:02:11.996 --> 02:02:13.776
Make him vomit! Please!

1911
02:02:13.886 --> 02:02:14.926
OK, hang on.

1912
02:02:17.166 --> 02:02:18.286
"Make a dog vomit."

1913
02:02:19.036 --> 02:02:20.246
Hang on.

1914
02:02:20.416 --> 02:02:23.086
We need saltwater.
Be right back.


1915
02:02:33.246 --> 02:02:34.336
He's not moving.

1916
02:02:34.536 --> 02:02:36.126
Daniel, help me.

1917
02:02:37.376 --> 02:02:38.746
Open his mouth.

1918
02:02:39.626 --> 02:02:40.666
Easy.

1919
02:02:50.206 --> 02:02:51.746
That's right.

1920
02:02:57.246 --> 02:02:58.456
That's good.

1921
02:03:01.126 --> 02:03:02.876
He's coming around.

1922
02:03:05.416 --> 02:03:07.956
- What's happening?
- He's going to vomit.


1923
02:03:13.836 --> 02:03:14.836
That's it.

1924
02:03:14.956 --> 02:03:16.286
He'll be OK.

1925
02:03:20.086 --> 02:03:21.456
Good dog.

1926
02:03:29.586 --> 02:03:32.376
He's OK, he's breathing.
Looking at us.


1927
02:03:37.786 --> 02:03:39.036
Can you explain?

1928
02:03:42.836 --> 02:03:44.246
You know, I...

1929
02:03:44.916 --> 02:03:46.956
I'd never heard about...

1930
02:03:48.416 --> 02:03:50.586
my dad's suicide attempt.

1931
02:03:51.726 --> 02:03:54.056
I'd never heard about...

1932
02:03:54.786 --> 02:03:57.536
the shrink, the medicine...

1933
02:03:58.456 --> 02:03:59.766
the vomit and aspirin.

1934
02:04:00.836 --> 02:04:03.536
When my mom talked about it,
I remembered something


1935
02:04:03.706 --> 02:04:05.286
from around that time.

1936
02:04:06.376 --> 02:04:07.496
One morning,

1937
02:04:07.726 --> 02:04:09.976
Snoop was lying on my bedroom floor.

1938
02:04:10.126 --> 02:04:12.286
Not moving.
He smelled like vomit.


1939
02:04:14.286 --> 02:04:16.336
I figured he'd vomited.

1940
02:04:17.786 --> 02:04:19.626
I cleaned his muzzle.

1941
02:04:20.666 --> 02:04:22.836
I figured he'd...

1942
02:04:23.336 --> 02:04:27.086
I don't know, caught a virus
or something, because...


1943
02:04:27.876 --> 02:04:30.496
he acted strange for days.

1944
02:04:30.666 --> 02:04:32.586
He just slept or drank.

1945
02:04:33.746 --> 02:04:37.996
See? Now I'm thinking
maybe he ate my dad's vomit,


1946
02:04:38.166 --> 02:04:39.666
and "that" made him sick,

1947
02:04:39.836 --> 02:04:41.876
and Mom told the truth!

1948
02:04:43.416 --> 02:04:46.246
So my experiment with the aspirin

1949
02:04:46.416 --> 02:04:48.376
was to see how he'd react.

1950
02:04:48.536 --> 02:04:49.626
And you saw.

1951
02:04:49.786 --> 02:04:53.416
He slept for 14 hours.
Now he's drinking all the time.


1952
02:04:53.586 --> 02:04:55.586
He smells exactly the same!

1953
02:04:56.206 --> 02:04:57.206
Everything!

1954
02:04:57.266 --> 02:04:59.306
Everything's exactly the same!

1955
02:05:00.876 --> 02:05:02.376
But since..

1956
02:05:03.016 --> 02:05:06.426
Since yesterday,
I'm not sure if I believe her or not.


1957
02:05:06.586 --> 02:05:08.456
I knew they fought, but...

1958
02:05:12.956 --> 02:05:14.496
It wasn't...

1959
02:05:15.626 --> 02:05:18.246
I didn't think it was that violent.

1960
02:05:20.246 --> 02:05:22.626
Your memories are all you're sure of,

1961
02:05:22.786 --> 02:05:24.786
and it's important to tell the jury.

1962
02:05:24.956 --> 02:05:26.746
But you're just a witness.

1963
02:05:26.916 --> 02:05:29.246
Do you think she could've killed him?

1964
02:05:32.746 --> 02:05:34.126
It's not for me to judge.

1965
02:05:34.286 --> 02:05:37.206
I know,
but you could at least tell me!


1966
02:05:37.436 --> 02:05:40.686
I can't answer that.
My role is to protect you...


1967
02:05:40.896 --> 02:05:42.686
Fucking help me!

1968
02:06:19.956 --> 02:06:21.166
Actually,

1969
02:06:21.336 --> 02:06:23.496
when we lack an element

1970
02:06:23.726 --> 02:06:26.176
to judge something,
and the lack is unbearable,


1971
02:06:27.336 --> 02:06:29.416
all we can do is decide.

1972
02:06:30.916 --> 02:06:32.086
You see?

1973
02:06:32.746 --> 02:06:35.586
To overcome doubt,
sometimes we have to...


1974
02:06:35.746 --> 02:06:38.416
decide to sway
one way rather than the other.


1975
02:06:40.376 --> 02:06:44.286
Since you need to believe one thing
but have two choices,


1976
02:06:44.456 --> 02:06:45.956
you must choose.

1977
02:06:47.036 --> 02:06:49.246
So you have to invent your belief?

1978
02:06:49.586 --> 02:06:51.626
Yes, well... in a sense.

1979
02:06:51.996 --> 02:06:54.666
So that means, 
I'm not sure...

1980
02:06:55.586 --> 02:06:59.206
and you're saying
I have to pretend I'm sure?


1981
02:06:59.996 --> 02:07:01.996
No, I'm saying decide.

1982
02:07:03.666 --> 02:07:05.246
That's different.

1983
02:07:36.876 --> 02:07:40.496
What strikes me is
we don't know who's more lyrical.


1984
02:07:40.706 --> 02:07:43.536
- The author or the character?
- Both, no doubt!


1985
02:07:43.706 --> 02:07:45.496
Voyter plays with confusion.

1986
02:07:45.666 --> 02:07:47.496
Her second book goes further,

1987
02:07:47.706 --> 02:07:50.876
telling how her father
couldn't stand the first.


1988
02:07:51.036 --> 02:07:52.166
Undoubtedly true.

1989
02:07:52.336 --> 02:07:56.086
The rift degenerates,
forcing her to leave her country.


1990
02:07:56.286 --> 02:08:00.376
Fearing her father's rage,
she falls prey to horrifying visions.


1991
02:08:00.536 --> 02:08:04.786
I found this troubling quote
in an interview. She says,


1992
02:08:05.126 --> 02:08:07.086
"My job is to cover the tracks,"

1993
02:08:07.246 --> 02:08:09.996
"so fiction can destroy reality."

1994
02:08:11.586 --> 02:08:13.416
Yes, and what excites people

1995
02:08:13.586 --> 02:08:15.666
about the Samuel Maleski case,

1996
02:08:15.836 --> 02:08:18.706
is that it seems to come
from one of her books.


1997
02:08:18.876 --> 02:08:21.336
It feels like
she's already written it.


1998
02:08:21.496 --> 02:08:25.166
Even the doubts around his death,
the way he died,


1999
02:08:25.336 --> 02:08:28.666
Voyter's murky personality,
the amoral, deceptive traits


2000
02:08:28.836 --> 02:08:30.206
she seems to overplay...

2001
02:08:30.376 --> 02:08:32.786
It all reads like her books.

2002
02:08:32.996 --> 02:08:35.416
I don't think it matters how he died.

2003
02:08:35.586 --> 02:08:39.166
The fact is, the idea of a writer
killing her husband


2004
02:08:39.336 --> 02:08:42.996
is far more compelling
than a teacher killing himself.


2005
02:10:53.706 --> 02:10:56.416
If I imagine my mother doing it,
I don't understand.


2006
02:10:58.786 --> 02:11:00.706
But if I imagine my father...

2007
02:11:02.956 --> 02:11:05.166
I think I can understand.

2008
02:11:11.376 --> 02:11:13.536
Prosecutor, any questions?

2009
02:11:16.496 --> 02:11:19.206
The experiment on his dog
proves nothing.


2010
02:11:19.376 --> 02:11:21.166
It's not documented.

2011
02:11:21.336 --> 02:11:24.246
More problematic
are these providential memories,


2012
02:11:24.416 --> 02:11:27.786
clearly jarred
by what he heard during the trial.


2013
02:11:28.416 --> 02:11:31.536
No event can be placed
convincingly on our timeline.


2014
02:11:31.706 --> 02:11:34.286
The time frame of 6 months
before Maleski's death


2015
02:11:34.456 --> 02:11:36.266
comes only from testimony

2016
02:11:36.416 --> 02:11:38.586
given by the defendant herself.

2017
02:11:42.336 --> 02:11:43.746
I'd like to know...

2018
02:11:50.416 --> 02:11:51.786
Did you ever wonder

2019
02:11:51.996 --> 02:11:54.956
if the overdose
your father supposedly took


2020
02:11:55.126 --> 02:11:58.536
might've resulted
not from a suicide attempt,


2021
02:11:58.706 --> 02:12:01.536
but from an attempt by your mother
to poison him?


2022
02:12:01.706 --> 02:12:04.416
I'm not accusing,
just making a point.


2023
02:12:04.586 --> 02:12:06.996
So, taking these speculations,

2024
02:12:07.166 --> 02:12:09.746
why choose one over the other?

2025
02:12:09.916 --> 02:12:13.996
Your memories speak
to the consequences, not the causes.


2026
02:12:15.206 --> 02:12:17.586
Yes, I thought about that, but...

2027
02:12:18.496 --> 02:12:20.916
I don't see
why she would've done it.


2028
02:12:21.456 --> 02:12:23.876
It feels like when we lack proof

2029
02:12:24.036 --> 02:12:26.706
to make us sure
how something happened,


2030
02:12:27.246 --> 02:12:30.166
we have to look further,
as the trial is doing.


2031
02:12:30.686 --> 02:12:34.226
When we've looked everywhere
and still don't understand


2032
02:12:34.436 --> 02:12:36.886
how the thing happened,

2033
02:12:37.036 --> 02:12:39.916
I think we have to ask
why it happened.


2034
02:12:44.916 --> 02:12:46.206
Thank you, Daniel.

2035
02:12:47.036 --> 02:12:48.206
Are you finished?

2036
02:12:56.586 --> 02:12:57.786
No.

2037
02:12:59.456 --> 02:13:01.206
I want to say something else.

2038
02:13:08.286 --> 02:13:12.706
Since my dog was sick for days,
Dad and I went to the vet.


2039
02:13:14.166 --> 02:13:16.286
Dad was really quiet in the car.

2040
02:13:16.456 --> 02:13:19.746
He didn't even play music.
He usually always does.


2041
02:13:22.336 --> 02:13:25.286
After a while,
he started talking about Snoop.


2042
02:13:26.876 --> 02:13:27.666
He said,

2043
02:13:27.846 --> 02:13:29.846
"You know, he could get sick."

2044
02:13:30.496 --> 02:13:33.746
"Even die. You know that.
You need to be ready."


2045
02:13:35.336 --> 02:13:36.956
I didn't want to hear that.

2046
02:13:37.706 --> 02:13:40.916
Snoop was doing better.
He was still young.


2047
02:13:41.146 --> 02:13:42.306
He'd never been sick.

2048
02:13:42.456 --> 02:13:44.706
I told him he wasn't going to die.

2049
02:13:46.806 --> 02:13:48.176
But he kept going.

2050
02:13:48.706 --> 02:13:52.956
He said, "You need to be aware of it.
It'll happen someday."


2051
02:13:53.916 --> 02:13:56.916
"And it's no wonder Snoop gets tired."

2052
02:13:57.086 --> 02:13:59.086
"He's not so young in dog years."

2053
02:14:02.286 --> 02:14:03.996
"Can you imagine his life?"

2054
02:14:06.166 --> 02:14:07.876
"He's not just any dog."

2055
02:14:08.836 --> 02:14:10.416
"He's a great dog."

2056
02:14:11.956 --> 02:14:13.836
"An outstanding dog."

2057
02:14:14.836 --> 02:14:17.786
"Think about it.
He anticipates your needs,"


2058
02:14:18.206 --> 02:14:20.416
"foresees your movements,"

2059
02:14:20.996 --> 02:14:22.746
"keeps you safe from danger."

2060
02:14:24.536 --> 02:14:26.786
"He spends his life
imagining your needs"


2061
02:14:26.956 --> 02:14:29.246
"thinking about what you can't see."

2062
02:14:32.836 --> 02:14:34.246
"Maybe he's tired."

2063
02:14:34.666 --> 02:14:36.336
"Always caring for others."

2064
02:14:37.126 --> 02:14:39.086
"Maybe one day, he'll be done."

2065
02:14:39.956 --> 02:14:41.246
"That could happen."

2066
02:14:46.336 --> 02:14:48.206
And I remember at the end,

2067
02:14:50.036 --> 02:14:51.996
he said, "One day",

2068
02:14:52.166 --> 02:14:55.126
"when it's time
for him to go, he'll go."


2069
02:14:56.246 --> 02:14:59.746
"You won't be able to help it.
Prepare yourself, it'll be hard."


2070
02:14:59.916 --> 02:15:02.336
"But it won't be
the end of your life."


2071
02:15:08.916 --> 02:15:10.456
He meant himself.

2072
02:15:11.286 --> 02:15:12.536
Now...

2073
02:15:13.956 --> 02:15:16.086
Now I know he meant himself.

2074
02:15:22.786 --> 02:15:25.956
I implore the jurors to bear in mind

2075
02:15:26.166 --> 02:15:28.416
this story is extremely subjective.

2076
02:15:28.836 --> 02:15:32.746
In no way does it qualify
as any form of proof.


2077
02:15:53.126 --> 02:15:56.996
Yes Serge, we are still
outside the courthouse in Grenoble.


2078
02:15:57.166 --> 02:16:00.086
The trial was scheduled
to end on Friday,


2079
02:16:00.246 --> 02:16:02.706
but Sandra Voyter's son Daniel

2080
02:16:02.876 --> 02:16:05.206
insisted on testifying again
this morning.


2081
02:16:05.376 --> 02:16:06.956
The jury is still...

2082
02:16:22.766 --> 02:16:23.786
Daniel.

2083
02:16:24.166 --> 02:16:27.746
Mrs Voyter, how do you feel...

2084
02:16:27.956 --> 02:16:30.086
after being acquitted?

2085
02:16:31.186 --> 02:16:34.766
There were too many words
in this trial.


2086
02:16:35.086 --> 02:16:36.496
I've nothing more to say.

2087
02:16:36.996 --> 02:16:40.246
I want to call
my son and go home.

2088
02:16:41.336 --> 02:16:45.376
Obviously I thank my lawyers,
who always believed in me.


2089
02:16:45.536 --> 02:16:48.166
Mr. Renzi, are you relieved?

2090
02:16:48.336 --> 02:16:50.496
I commend the jury,

2091
02:16:50.836 --> 02:16:53.416
who saw Sandra Voyter as she is...

2092
02:17:55.166 --> 02:17:57.036
Marge, it's Sandra.

2093
02:17:59.126 --> 02:18:01.666
Yes, it's incredible, we're relieved.

2094
02:18:05.706 --> 02:18:07.916
Does Daniel want to talk to me?

2095
02:18:10.376 --> 02:18:12.626
Of course, he must be tired,

2096
02:18:12.856 --> 02:18:14.056
I understand.

2097
02:18:15.876 --> 02:18:18.786
Does he mind if I come home tonight?

2098
02:18:19.016 --> 02:18:20.886
Would he prefer tomorrow, or...

2099
02:18:25.786 --> 02:18:27.496
OK, OK.

2100
02:18:28.206 --> 02:18:31.786
We'll get some dinner,
then I'll be home. See you then.


2101
02:18:35.336 --> 02:18:36.786
I need a drink.

2102
02:18:41.356 --> 02:18:42.606
Another!

2103
02:18:51.416 --> 02:18:52.786
Do you always...

2104
02:18:52.956 --> 02:18:56.086
When you win,
do you always do this?


2105
02:18:56.246 --> 02:18:57.626
We never win.

2106
02:18:59.336 --> 02:19:02.126
That's the fucking first time
in our life we win!


2107
02:19:02.286 --> 02:19:03.626
- No!
- Yes, of course!


2108
02:19:03.786 --> 02:19:05.786
You told me you're a good lawyer.

2109
02:19:09.286 --> 02:19:10.536
No, it's not true!

2110
02:19:10.656 --> 02:19:11.656
It's not spicy.

2111
02:19:11.746 --> 02:19:13.536
You have to try this, really.

2112
02:19:13.746 --> 02:19:15.036
We ate too much.

2113
02:19:15.206 --> 02:19:16.286
I'm gonna throw up.

2114
02:19:16.496 --> 02:19:18.126
A quick smoke first.

2115
02:19:18.456 --> 02:19:19.536
Be right back.

2116
02:19:24.286 --> 02:19:25.586
You first.

2117
02:19:39.456 --> 02:19:41.246
It's not so easy, huh?

2118
02:19:42.916 --> 02:19:44.746
With all the bones, and...

2119
02:19:49.376 --> 02:19:50.586
After this, we go?

2120
02:19:50.916 --> 02:19:52.456
Ready to go home?

2121
02:19:53.286 --> 02:19:55.876
I can drive, I can drive you.

2122
02:19:57.036 --> 02:19:58.086
One more.

2123
02:19:58.876 --> 02:20:00.286
For the road.

2124
02:20:01.626 --> 02:20:03.496
Of course, for the driver.

2125
02:20:04.586 --> 02:20:05.666
Same?

2126
02:20:13.836 --> 02:20:15.536
Can I just get

2127
02:20:15.746 --> 02:20:17.956
two more of these? Thanks.

2128
02:20:34.126 --> 02:20:35.166
To you.

2129
02:20:50.456 --> 02:20:51.626
Are you alright?

2130
02:20:55.836 --> 02:20:57.036
Tell me.

2131
02:20:57.746 --> 02:20:59.746
I just, I thought...

2132
02:21:01.336 --> 02:21:03.876
I thought I'd feel relieved.

2133
02:21:07.536 --> 02:21:09.376
It doesn't come right away.

2134
02:21:11.496 --> 02:21:12.666
Sure?

2135
02:21:12.836 --> 02:21:13.916
Not sure.

2136
02:21:17.286 --> 02:21:19.746
It's just, you know,
when you lose, you lose.


2137
02:21:20.336 --> 02:21:22.286
It's the worst thing that can happen,

2138
02:21:22.456 --> 02:21:23.876
and if you win...

2139
02:21:26.456 --> 02:21:29.416
you expect some reward.

2140
02:21:30.956 --> 02:21:32.416
But there isn't any.

2141
02:21:33.246 --> 02:21:34.416
It's just...

2142
02:21:36.286 --> 02:21:37.706
It's just over.

2143
02:21:42.666 --> 02:21:45.456
Maybe sometimes,
we expect too much.


2144
02:21:48.746 --> 02:21:49.996
Yeah, maybe.

2145
02:22:55.746 --> 02:22:56.996
Hi.

2146
02:22:57.996 --> 02:22:59.336
Sorry.

2147
02:23:01.286 --> 02:23:03.876
He tried to wait up but fell asleep.

2148
02:23:53.166 --> 02:23:54.706
I'll be going now.

2149
02:23:54.876 --> 02:23:56.086
Not staying over?

2150
02:23:56.246 --> 02:23:58.126
No, I'll leave you be.

2151
02:24:04.456 --> 02:24:05.626
- Goodbye.
- Goodbye.


2152
02:24:22.786 --> 02:24:24.916
I was afraid of you coming home.

2153
02:24:26.666 --> 02:24:29.786
Me too,
I was afraid to come home.